node.text:
Coalsack Dark Nebula, "coming out" of a chimney
.
Photo credit: @darkeyesopen Check out photographer's page!
.
The Coalsack is the most prominent dark nebula in the sky, easily visible with the naked eye. It’s located east of Acrux, which is the bright star at the bottom of the Southern Cross
.
Tag @the.astronomy.daily to feature your photos!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Astronomy Daily in International Space Station.

node.text:
Colorful blue lights dance across the Earth’s atmosphere captured by @Thom_Astro aboard the International Space Station
.
Credit: ESA via @nasa
.
Incoming energy and particles from the sun interacting with Earth’s magnetic field causing bursts of light and color across the magnetosphere. In a glowing aurora, we see billions of these individual collisions of energy lighting up the sky – a breathtaking phenomenon that can also be observed from space
.
Tag @the.astronomy.daily to feature your photos!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Astronomy Daily on September 01, 2021 tagging @rami_astro. May be an image of planet.

node.text:
The Moons of Saturn
.
Photo credit: @rami_astro Check out photographer's page!
.
Gear: Canon 90D and a Celestron EDGE HD C11. EXIF: Saturn itself was extracted from a 3 minutes video. A stack of 1500 frames was done with sharpening to bring up details. The Moons of Saturn are a series of 10 seconds long exposures, stacked all in Photoshop using the mean method
.
Tag @the.astronomy.daily to feature your photos!

node.text:
Starry night, from Himachal Pradesh, India
.
Photo credit: @simexposure Check out photographer's page!
.
Quote "Even though we may be gazing at the same night sky from different parts of the country, the overall experience of being where you are will depend on many little elements. From the cup of masala tea you had before adventuring out into a cold night to the person beside you who trusted you to not get yourselves lost in an unfamiliar area."
.
Tag @the.astronomy.daily to feature your photos!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Astronomy Daily in Sacramento, California with @nightskyflying. May be an image of planet, sky and text.

node.text:
Saturn, imaged by @nightskyflying
.
Quote "This here is a shot from a few nights back using just a single run of data, but it was some pretty solid data allowing me to pull out a lot of detail. I boosted the colors a bit unnaturally to bring out the definition in the hexagon at the north pole. The starfield in the background is from a separate shot and then blended together during processing."
.
Tag @the.astronomy.daily to feature your photos!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Astronomy Daily in Houston, Texas with @adamkylejackson. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
“Once in a Blue Moon”
.
Credit: @adamkylejackson Check out photographer's page!
.
Quote "Hanging out in the backyard with a Tripod, telescope, and D750 on my pool deck melting away in the 80 degrees Houston, Texas dewpoint night, fogging up every surface of glass on the lens, I managed to capture the Blue Sturgeon Moon 2021 at around 320mm effective focal length. "
.
Tag @the.astronomy.daily to feature your photos!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Astronomy Daily on August 25, 2021 tagging @astronophilos. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
“Blue Conjunction"
.
Credit: @astronophilos Check out photographer's page!
.
Quote "This weekend, an unusual event happened: Jupiter had an appointment with a full blue moon! The name given to this Moon is not representative of its real color. It is so called when 13 full Moons occur instead of 12 normally. Jupiter was shining not far from there, which gave a startling show in our night sky."
.
Tag @the.astronomy.daily to feature your photos!
